trg_text: National Student Financial Aid Scheme (NSFAS) Cabinet received a briefing from the Minister of Higher Education, Science and Technology, Dr Blade Nzimande, on the current funding shortfall challenges faced by the NSFA These challenges have delayed the finalization of the registration of first-year university student The COVID-19 pandemic has exacerbated the challenges of the schem Some of these being the extended academic year and a number of students qualifying for the fund due to parents having lost their job To resolve this challenge, Cabinet approved additional funding and the details of which will be unpacked by Minister Nzimande immediately after this briefin Cabinet has directed that further work must be done to find a more sustainable approach to fund students for their tertiary educatio Cabinet remains committed to ensuring that all deserving students are not excluded due to the lack of funding Draft Position Paper for Land Administration and Land Tenure Reforms in Communal Areas Cabinet approved the draft Position Paper on Land Administration and Land Tenure Reforms in Communal Areas for further consultations with relevant stakeholder The proposed reforms provide a legal framework to initiate the process of transferring communal land to persons or communities whose tenure of land is legally insecur These reforms will also expand the communal asset base to empower communities to engage in cultural, social and economic activities of their choic The consultations will culminate in the convening of the envisaged National Land Summit Vaccine procurement Cabinet received a briefing by Health Minister Zwelini Mkhize and Finance Minister Tito Mboweni regarding contract negotiations for vaccine acquisition with different pharmaceutical companie Cabinet considered some of the difficult terms in the contracts that are not aligned to the provisions of the Public Finance Management Act, 1999 (Act 1 of 1999) and acknowledged the deviations already granted by National Treasury in the interests of the lives of South African The deviations included prepayment provisions to ensure that South Africans have access to the vaccines as soon as possibl Cabinet supported the efforts of National Treasury and the National Department of Health to continue with the negotiations and ensure quick access to vaccines for all National State of Disaster Cabinet approved the extension of National State of Disaster to 15 April 2021.

src_text: Proudly South African ke lekala la Kgoro ya Kgwebi ano, Intaseteri le Phadi an Samiti e be e ga wa thwii go t wa dikgokaganong t a go fapafapana t a inthanete le leago go kgont ha kgathotema yeo e nabilego dipoledi anon Pont ho ye e swerwego ka inthanete e kgont hit e dikhamphani go kwalakwat a dit welet wa le ditirelo t a t ona ka bideo e nnyane gape e kgont hit ego gore go be le kopano ye e swerwego ka inthanete magareng ga bakgathatema bao ba bego ba na le kgahlego ya go tsenela kgwebi ano le kgwebo e itsen Kabinete e ipilet a go maAfrika Borwa le dikgwebo go thekga dit welet wa le ditirelo t eo di hlamilwego ka mo nageng, kudu mo nakong ya tso olo o ya ikonomi, go t wet a pele kgolo ya ikonomi le tlhamo ya me omo Ketelo Lefelong la Bobolokelo la Biovac Motlat apresidente David Mabuza o etet e lefelo la bobolokelo la Biovac go la Midrand, Gauteng, ka Labobedi la 2 Hlakola 2021 bjalo ka karolo ya mo omo wa Komiti ya Ditona go Meento ya COVID-19, yeo e hlokomet ego gore go phatlalat wa ga lenaneo la go entela go a atleg Setheo sa Biovac, elego khamphani ya t a bokhemese yeo elego Cape Town, beng ba yona ke mmu o le lekala la poraebet Yona e hlamilwe ka 2003 gomme e rwele maikarabelo a mananeo a go hlabela mo tlhabollong ya meento, mmogo le go lota le go phatlalat a meento go ya mafelong ao a fapafapanego a go entel Mo mengwageng yeo e fetilego, Biovac e dirile sekgoba seo se lekanego sa go lota le go ABA meent Kabinete e kgotsofadit we ke go t ea karolo ga yona ge go etla lenaneong la kabo ya meento gape le mo omo woo e o dirago mmogo le dikhemese t e dingwe go t welet a meento ya COVID-14.
trg_text: Occupational Health and Safety (OHS) Bill of 2020 Cabinet approved the publication of the OHS Bill 2020 for public consultatio The Bill seeks to amend the OHS Act, 1993 (Act 85 of 1993) and align it to international trend It also seeks to strengthen the safety measures of workers in their respective workplace The Bill introduces the provisions that empower employees to withhold their labour should they feel the environment is dangerous and unsafe, without being victimized by the employers Housing Consumer Protection Bill Cabinet approved the submission of the Housing Consumer Protection Bill for tabling in Parliamen The Bill repeals the Housing Consumers Protection Measures Act, 1998 (Act 95 of 1998).
